In short I found this to be a really boring movie
column4:
it managed to make me not care about any of the new characters and so have no interest or investment in what happens to them.

The plot holes have been well-documented in other reviews and are so glaring as you watch the movie that they take you out of the moment and disengaged from the film. Although some people seem to have wasted considerable time trying to subsequently work out explanations for these plot holes
column5: if they mean you don\'t enjoy the film whilst you are watching it
column6:
what is the point?

For some reason the ponderous chase plot unfortunately reminded me of the OJ police chase from 94\' and just about as ridiculous.

Lot\'s been said about the juvenile casino side plot and I so I don\'t need to explain why I found myself constantly rolling my eyes and looking away from the screen often during this portion of the movie.

As has also often been noted
column7:
Rey is two-dimensional with no interesting back story/characteristics/development; I like Daisy Ridley as an actress - but what a god awful character for her to work with :(

I also hate what they did to Domnhall Gleeson in this
column8:
I felt so embarrassed for him; he is a way better actor then the dreadful comedic \'Hux\' role. It actually made me sad to see him portrayed this way...

My overall impressions:
- The acting was good in places (especially Hamill) but the characters (especially Rey) were poorly written. Some of the dialogue was dreadful to the point of making me cringe.
- Visually
